#design #edges

> <- in a file = forward edge in DB; src always points to dst regardless of declaration side.

Edge direction convention — critical to understand before touching store or parser.

In a .eshp FILE:
  -> target   means this note points TO target   (outgoing)
  <- source   means source points TO this note   (incoming / reverse declaration)

In the SQLITE edges table:
  ALL edges are stored as (src, rel, dst) — always forward direction.

So a <- source line in note X is stored as: INSERT INTO edges(src=source, rel=..., dst=X)
This means you can declare a relationship from either side of the link,
but the DB always represents it as src → dst.

upsert_note() deletes edges WHERE src=slug before re-inserting (outgoing).
It also deletes orphan incoming edges: WHERE dst=slug AND src NOT IN (SELECT slug FROM notes).
This means malformed <- lines (ghost src slugs) self-heal on the next sync.
It does NOT delete valid edges pointed at this note by other notes (those persist).

TRAP: If you write '<- rel slug' instead of '<- slug', the whole string 'rel slug'
becomes the src — creating a ghost node with a space in its slug. It won't appear
in the notes table so cytoscape (and anything else iterating notes) will miss it.
The orphan cleanup in upsert_note catches this on re-sync.

